studyDesigns.name: Study Design
studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: Phase I - Single Arm Exercise
arms.description: 15 subjects with mild dementia and cognitive impairments participate in a single arm 6 weeks remote exercise intervention using the Exergaming platform, twice per week for approximately 30 minutes

arms.name: Phase II - Remote Exercise Intervention
arms.description: Subjects receive the Exergaming system at home and perform 24 exercise sessions remotely over 12 weeks, twice per week for approximately 30 minutes

arms.name: Phase II - Supervised Exercise Control
arms.description: Subjects perform the 24 exercise sessions in person under supervision with the Exergaming system over 12 weeks, twice per week for approximately 30 minutes

studyCohorts.name: Phase I Participants
studyCohorts.characteristic: 15 subjects with mild dementia and cognitive impairments (MoCA score 20-26) participating in pilot 6-week program

studyCohorts.name: Phase II Participants
studyCohorts.characteristic: 100 subjects with mild dementia and cognitive impairments (MoCA score 20-26) participating in 12-week RCT

eligibilityCriteria.name: Inability to engage safely in exercise program

objectives.name: Primary Technology Development Objective
objectives.text: To help design and validate a novel technology to remotely provide exercise intervention for people at risk or with some level of dementia

objectives.name: Remote Assessment Objective
objectives.text: To enable remote assessment of cognitive-motor performance via wearable sensors through playing a simple interactive game named iTMT

objectives.name: Cognitive Function Preservation Objective
objectives.text: To preserve cognitive function in people with MCI through remote exercise intervention

objectives.name: Balance and Mobility Improvement Objective
objectives.text: To improve balance and cognition during distractive conditioning while the exercise is remotely supervised by a telemedicine interface

objectives.name: Fear of Falling Reduction Objective
objectives.text: To reduce fear of falling in older adults with mild cognitive impairment

objectives.name: Independent Living Promotion Objective
objectives.text: To promote independent living and reduce costs associated with consequence of cognitive-motor decline including falls and frailty

objectives.name: Sex Difference Exploratory Objective
objectives.text: To examine whether the benefit of exercise is dependent on sex (sex as biological factor)

objectives.name: Confounder Correlation Exploratory Objective
objectives.text: To determine whether the magnitude of gain is correlated with confounders including age, baseline cognitive performance, baseline motor performance, and BMI

endpoints.name: Center of Mass Sway
endpoints.text: Change in center of mass (COM) sway area in medial-lateral direction during eyes-open stance at 6 weeks compared to baseline

endpoints.name: Remote Exercise Feasibility
endpoints.text: Feasibility of remotely-supervised exercise platform measured by completion rate of exercise sessions

endpoints.name: Technology Acceptability
endpoints.text: Acceptability of the teleexergame platform measured by acceptability questionnaire at follow up visit

endpoints.name: iTMT Cognitive Performance
endpoints.text: Cognitive-motor performance assessed via iTMT (interactive Trail Making Test) using wearable sensors

endpoints.name: Remote Motor Assessment
endpoints.text: Motor performance parameters captured remotely via wearable sensor system

endpoints.name: Trail Making Test A
endpoints.text: Change from baseline in Trail-Making Test A (TMT-A) score post exercise

endpoints.name: MoCA Score
endpoints.text: Change from baseline in Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) score

endpoints.name: Balance Assessment
endpoints.text: Balance quantified using BalanSens measuring ankle and hip motion in 3D, 2D COM sway, and RCI in ML and AP directions during Romberg protocol

endpoints.name: Gait Parameters
endpoints.text: Spatio-temporal gait parameters including velocity, stride length, stride time, double support, single support, stride-to-stride variability, and gait initiation assessed using LegSys

endpoints.name: Fear of Falling
endpoints.text: Change from baseline in Falls Efficacy Scale-International (FES-I) score

endpoints.name: Daily Physical Activity
endpoints.text: Physical activity parameters including number of steps, duration of sitting, standing, walking and lying, postural transitions measured by PAMSys over 48 hours

endpoints.name: Quality of Life
endpoints.text: Change from baseline in quality of life measured by PROMIS Global scale

endpoints.name: Sex-Based Balance Improvement
endpoints.text: Comparison of gain in balance improvement between male and female participants

endpoints.name: Confounder Correlation Analysis
endpoints.text: Correlation of magnitude of gain with confounders including age, baseline cognitive performance, baseline motor performance, and BMI using Spearman correlation coefficient

studyInterventions.name: Tele-exergaming Exercise Intervention
studyInterventions.description: Remote in-home exercise system for adults with mild cognitive impairment or mild dementia designed to improve balance and cognition during distractive conditioning while remotely supervised via telemedicine interface

studyInterventions.name: Supervised Exercise Intervention
studyInterventions.description: Exercise intervention performed in a supervised condition (control group in Phase II RCT)

activities.name: History and Physical Examination
activities.description: A standard physical examination will be performed at screening. Record age, gender, presence of diabetes and its type and duration, diabetic treatment, prior foot ulcers, prior amputations or foot surgeries, co-existing medical conditions. Use Kaplan Co-morbidity Index to score disease severity.

activities.name: Informed Consent
activities.description: Obtain written informed consent from participant prior to any study related procedures

activities.name: Medical History
activities.description: Record socio-demographics (age, gender, BMI, education, marital status) and medical history (health status including comorbidities, history of falls, history of hospitalization, prior surgery, duration of diagnosed MCI, co-existing medical conditions, hearing and visual performance, frailty status), medication use

activities.name: Socio-demographics
activities.description: Record age, gender, BMI, education, marital status and other demographic information

activities.name: Social Factors
activities.description: Evaluate marital status, years of education, type of work, tobacco history (pack years, current smoker, current use of chewing tobacco, previous smoker, no tobacco history)

activities.name: Quality of Life (Promise Global)
activities.description: Health related questionnaire for quality of life assessment

activities.name: Demographics
activities.description: Demographics questionnaire

activities.name: Beck Anxiety Scale
activities.description: Anxiety assessment questionnaire

activities.name: Pain-Mobility
activities.description: Pain and mobility assessment questionnaire

activities.name: Fear of Falling (FES-I)
activities.description: Falls Efficacy Scale - International for fear of falling assessment

activities.name: Frailty (Fried Frailty)
activities.description: Fried Frailty criteria assessment (Weight loss >10 pounds in preceding year; Grip strength; Low levels of physical activity; 15 foot walk time; Exhaustion)

activities.name: MOCA for cognitive status
activities.description: Montreal Cognitive Assessment for cognitive status evaluation

activities.name: Depression (CES-D)
activities.description: Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale

activities.name: Trail-making task A and B
activities.description: Trail-Making Test A and B for cognitive assessment

activities.name: LifeSpace
activities.description: LifeSpace questionnaire for mobility assessment

activities.name: ePro Lawton and Katz Scale
activities.description: Electronic patient reported outcome for daily activities assessment using Lawton and Katz Scale

activities.name: Acceptability questionnaire
activities.description: Questionnaire to assess acceptability of the intervention at follow up visit

activities.name: Peripheral Neuropathy (VPT testing)
activities.description: Vibration Perception Threshold (VPT) testing, evaluated at the distal great toe, heel and 5th metatarsal

activities.name: Standard foot questionnaire
activities.description: Standard foot questionnaire to assess any potential limitation which may influence the ability of participants to perform iTMT using ankle-foot trail making

activities.name: Frailty status (Fried Frailty criteria)
activities.description: Examine frailty status using Fried Frailty criteria

activities.name: Height and weight measurement
activities.description: Measure height and weight to determine body mass index

activities.name: Gait assessment (LegSys sensors)
activities.description: Gait performance assessed using validated body worn sensors (LegSys, Biosensics LLC). Device uses five sensor modules attached to right and left anterior shins, right and left anterior thighs, and posteriorly to the lower back. Parameters estimated: velocity, stride length, stride time, double support, single support, stride-to-stride variability, and gait initiation. Gait assessed over 20 meters at habitual and maximum speed.

activities.name: Balance assessment (BalanSens sensors)
activities.description: Balance quantified using validated body worn sensors (BalanSens, Biosensics LLC). System measures ankle and hip motion in 3D, 2D COM sway and RCI in ML and AP directions. Balance assessed according to Romberg protocol during eyes-open and eyes-closed condition during double, semi-tandem, and full tandem stances.

activities.name: Timed-up-and-go (TUG)
activities.description: Subject stands up from a chair, walks 3 meters, walks back to the chair, and sits down as fast and safely as possible

activities.name: Upper Extremity Test (arm motion)
activities.description: Measure arm motion using validated wearable sensor system (LegSys). One sensor placed on wrist to capture arm motion. Subject flexes and extends arm for 20 seconds at fast speed, then repeats while counting backwards (dual task).

activities.name: PAMSys wearable device (48 hours)
activities.description: Wearable device (PAMSys) measuring number of steps taken, duration of sitting, standing, walking and lying, time taken and number of transitions from sit to stand, and walking speed for 48 hours. Device attached to pendant worn around neck.

activities.name: Exergaming platform exercise program
activities.description: Exercise program using Exergaming platform, twice per week for approximately 30 minutes. Includes ankle reaching tasks in upward-downward direction and side-ward reaching task, progressing to diagonal directions and motor-cognitive tasks.

activities.name: Motor-Cognitive Exercise program (TMT)
activities.description: Motor-cognitive exercise including working memory inspired from paper-pencil Trail-Making test (TMT). Includes three levels of motor-cognitive complexities: Fixed-order TMT, Random-order TMT, and Number-Letter-order TMT.

activities.name: Phone calls (3 and 6 months post follow-up)
activities.description: Contact subjects at three and six months after follow up visit to ask about accidental falls and other health questions

activities.name: Photos and media collection
activities.description: Take photos, film videos and/or record audio during visits to monitor progress. May be used for scientific publications/oral presentations with face covered per journal policy.

notes.text: Phase I: 15 subjects with mild dementia and cognitive impairments in single arm 6 weeks remote exercise intervention
Phase II: 100 subjects randomized to intervention or control group for 12 weeks exercise program
Inclusion: MoCA score 20-26, ambulatory (able to walk 20m), living independently with caregiver
Exclusion: Immobility, severe cognitive impairment (MoCA < 20), stroke, Parkinson disease, psychiatric conditions
Participants compensated $50 per baseline/follow-up visit and $10 per exercise session

conditions.name: MCI/Mild Dementia Diagnosis
conditions.text: Formal diagnosis of MCI or mild dementia, or MoCA score between 20-26

conditions.name: Ambulatory Status
conditions.text: Able to walk a distance of 20m with or without walking assistance

conditions.name: Living Situation Requirement
conditions.text: Living independently in a residential home with a caregiver/informant

conditions.name: TMT Task Mastery Criteria
conditions.text: Execution of all TMT within 5 minutes with less than two errors to achieve next complexity level

conditions.name: Mobility Disorder Exclusion
conditions.text: Immobility or major mobility disorder or inability to engage safely in the proposed weight-bearing exercise program

transitionRules.name: Phase I Week 1 to Week 2 Transition
transitionRules.text: After completing first two sessions of ankle reaching tasks in upward-downward and side-ward directions, diagonal reaching tasks are added in sessions 3 and 4

transitionRules.name: Phase I Week 2 to Week 3 Transition
transitionRules.text: From session 5 (week 3), motor-cognitive tasks are added to the exercise program

transitionRules.name: Phase II Week 2 to Week 4 Transition
transitionRules.text: Starting the 5th session (week 4), reaching tasks on diagonal directions are added

transitionRules.name: Phase II Week 4 to Week 6 Transition
transitionRules.text: From the 11th session (week 6), motor-cognitive tasks are added

transitionRules.name: TMT Complexity Level Progression
transitionRules.text: When subject masters one level (execution of all TMT within 5 minutes with less than two errors), they achieve the next complexity level

transitionRules.name: Phase II Randomization
transitionRules.text: 100 subjects will be randomized into either intervention (remote) or control (supervised in-person) group

transitionRules.name: Screening to Treatment Transition
transitionRules.text: Subject must meet all eligibility criteria including MoCA score 20-26, ambulatory status, and living independently with caregiver

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Voluntary Withdrawal
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Participation is entirely voluntary and the participants could stop/leave the study at any time

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Phase I Study Completion
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Completion of 6 week exercise program including baseline, 12 intervention sessions, 3 weeks follow up, and 6 weeks follow up

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Phase II Study Completion
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Completion of 12 week exercise program including baseline, 24 exercise sessions, 6 weeks follow up, 12 weeks follow up, 6 months follow up, and 12 month follow up

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Travelling Difficulties
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Subject may drop out due to travelling difficulties as noted in pilot program
